<TITLE> USAID offers to help govt assess Sundarbans damage </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 28 (bdnews24.com) - USAID has said it is interested to work with the government to asses the impact of the tropical Cyclone Sidr on the Sundarbans, a world heritage site. In a letter to environment and forest adviser CS Karim, USAID mission director Denise Rollins said her agency was interested to be part of the assessment if the government took the initiative. "If you agree in principle with the need for this assessment, USAID offers to take the lead to coordinate the design, implementation and funding requirements for the assessment," the Nov 27 letter read. "The Sundarbans bear the glory of national as well as global heritage and conservation of this heritage should get a prime and immediate priority," it said. The US agency's letter came in response to Karim's recent statement that all the conservation infrastructures in the Sundarbans, the largest mangrove forest in the world, have been damaged by the Sidr. b
